rly character formation; South African Bernard Lategan, whose New Testament studies became entangled on both sides of his country’s battles over apartheid; and Linda Nochlin, whose essay “Why Have There Been No Great Women Artists?” virtually created the field of feminist art history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aIntellectual freedom. 0aLearning and scholarship. 7aEDUCATION / Philosophy, Theory & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aAcademic.  aArt history.  aBernard Lategan.  aBiblical studies.  aDemocracy.  aEkphrasis.  aEnlightenment.  aEvidence.  aFeminism.  aFootnote.  aFreedom.  aHermeneutics.  aHigher education.  aHistory.  aLinda Nochlin.  aModernity.  aResearch.  aScholarship.  aUniversity.  aW. E. B. Du Bois.  aapartheid.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069005740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067425031440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674250314423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674250314/original  a978-3-11-069005-7  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK